#: origin/heimdal.txt:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "===================================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:420
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"4. MASTER KDC SERVER CONFIGURATION:\n"
"===================================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:422 origin/heimdal.txt:731
#, no-wrap
msgid "------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:424
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating the /etc/heimdal Directory:\n"
"------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:427
msgid "Create the /etc/heimdal configuration directory with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:429
msgid "install -d -m 755 /etc/heimdal"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:430 origin/heimdal.txt:478 origin/heimdal.txt:721
#, no-wrap
msgid "--------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:432
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating /etc/heimdal/krb5.conf:\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:435
msgid "Create the kerberos configuration file with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:440 origin/heimdal.txt:903
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cat > /etc/heimdal/krb5.conf << \"EOF\"\n"
"[libdefaults]\n"
"    default_realm = LFS.ORG\n"
"    encrypt = true\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:447 origin/heimdal.txt:910
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[realms]\n"
"    LFS.ORG = {\n"
"        kdc = belgarath.lfs.org\n"
"        admin_server = belgarath.lfs.org\n"
"        kpasswd_server = belgarath.lfs.org\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:450 origin/heimdal.txt:913
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[domain_realm]\n"
"    .lfs.org = LFS.ORG\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:455 origin/heimdal.txt:918
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[logging]\n"
"    kdc = FILE:/var/log/kdc.log\n"
"    admin_server = FILE:/var/log/kadmin.log\n"
"    default = FILE:/var/log/krb.log\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:457 origin/heimdal.txt:666 origin/heimdal.txt:785 origin/heimdal.txt:920
msgid "EOF"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:461
msgid ""
"You will need to substitute your domain and proper hostname for the "
"occurances of the belgarath and lfs.org names. Here's an explanation of the "
"krb5.conf parameters."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:465
msgid ""
"default_realm should be the name of your domain changed to ALL CAPS. This "
"isn't required, but both Heimdal and MIT recommend it. Should you desire a "
"name other than capitalized domainname, well, YOYO."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:470
msgid ""
"encrypt = true provides encryption of all traffic between kerberized clients "
"and servers. It's not necessary and can be left off. If you leave it off, "
"you can encrypt all traffic from the client to the server using a switch on "
"the client program instead. You decide how you want it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:473
msgid ""
"The [realms] parameters tell the client programs where to look for the KDC "
"authentication services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:475
msgid "The [domain_realm] section maps a domain to a realm."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:477
msgid "The [logging] section is optional. I'm a log freak, so I want it in there."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:480
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating /var/lib/heimdal/m-key:\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:483
msgid "Store the master password in a key file using the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:486
msgid "install -d -m 755 /var/lib/heimdal kstash"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:489
msgid ""
"You'll be prompted to enter, then verify the password. The key file should "
"be created and have 600 (root read/write only) permissions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:490 origin/heimdal.txt:548
#, no-wrap
msgid "--------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:492
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating the KDC database:\n"
"--------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:502
msgid ""
"Create the KDC database by \"connecting\" to the as-yet-not-created database "
"in \"local\" mode. What I mean by this is, we are going to run the kadmin "
"program, which \"connects\" to the KDC database and allows administrative "
"updates and modifications. But there's no database yet! Running kadmin with "
"a \"-l\" switch allows us to \"connect\" to the database (from the local "
"host only), even if the database doesn't exist. Run the following commands, "
"and choose the defaults for now. You can go in later and change the "
"defaults, should you feel the need."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:504 origin/heimdal.txt:573
msgid "kadmin -l"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:506
msgid "At the \"kadmin>\" prompt, issue the following statement:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:508
msgid "init LFS.ORG"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:512
msgid ""
"Of course, substitute the realm name you identified in the \"default_realm\" "
"parameter of the [libdefaults] section of the krb5.conf file you created "
"earlier."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:516
msgid ""
"After accepting the defaults about the realm ticket life, you will be back "
"at the \"kadmin>\" prompt. You've now created the database. You can open up "
"another terminal and look in the /var/lib/heimdal directory to confirm this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:523
msgid ""
"Now we need to populate the database with principles (users). You should "
"create at least one for now. Use your regular login name or \"root\". You "
"need to decide what you want to use as an admin user for the day-to-day "
"admin duties of the KDC. It's not important now, just something to think "
"about for when the time comes to create the ACL's. For now, just use your "
"regular login name or root. (you should still be at the \"kadmin>\" prompt)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:525
msgid "add loginname"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:531
msgid ""
"Of course, substitute some valid login name. Just press enter to choose the "
"default choices during the add user routine (or, if you're bold and know "
"what you're doing, modify the defaults). Choose a password carefully, this "
"will be the password you'll use to authenticate to the KDC. You can always "
"change your password later, however."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:534
msgid ""
"There's enough done now to test the installation. So, exit the kadmin "
"program (use quit or exit) and return back to the unix prompt."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:537
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Starting the KDC Daemon:\n"
"------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:543
msgid ""
"We'll start the KDC daemon manually right now, just to test out the "
"installation. After you're convinced you want to use kerberos, you can "
"install and use the init script provided later in the instructions. Start "
"the daemon with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:545
msgid "/usr/sbin/kdc &"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:547
msgid "A \"ps -ef | grep kdc\" listing should show the daemon running."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:550
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Getting and Listing a TGT:\n"
"--------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:553
msgid "Attempt to get a TGT (ticket-granting-ticket) with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:555
msgid "kinit loginname"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:559
msgid ""
"Of course, use the login name you used when you added it into the database.  "
"You will be prompted for the password you created. After you get your "
"ticket, you can list it with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:561
msgid "klist"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:563
msgid "Information about the ticket should be displayed on the screen."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:564 origin/heimdal.txt:924 origin/heimdal.txt:1152
#, no-wrap
msgid "----------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:566 origin/heimdal.txt:926
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating /etc/heimdal/krb5.keytab:\n"
"----------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:571
msgid ""
"The KDC server and any machine running kerberized server daemons must have a "
"host key installed. To create the host key (keytab file), issue the "
"following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:575
msgid ""
"This connects to the database again in \"local\" mode. At the \"kadmin>\" "
"prompt:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:577
msgid "add --random-key host/belgarath.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:583
msgid ""
"Of course, substitute the proper hostname and domainname. *Do* leave the "
"word \"host\" as it is. Only substitute the \"belgarath.lfs.org\". Again, "
"choose the defaults when prompted. You will return back to the \"kadmin>\" "
"prompt. To actually export the data to a keytab file, type the following at "
"the \"kadmin>\" prompt:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:585
msgid "ext host/belgarath.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:591
msgid ""
"Of course, make the appropriate substitutions. This should have created two "
"files in /etc/heimdal; krb5.keytab (kerberos 5) and srvtab (kerberos "
"4). BOTH FILES SHOULD HAVE 600 (root rw only) PERMISSIONS. Keeping the "
"keytab files from public access is crucial to the overall security of the "
"kerberos installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:594
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Testing the keytab file:\n"
"------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:598
msgid ""
"To test the functionality of the keytab file, issue the following command "
"from the unix prompt:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:600
msgid "ktutil list"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:603
msgid ""
"This should dump a list of the host principal, along with the encryption "
"methods used to access the principal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:606
msgid ""
"At this point, if everything has been successful so far, you can feel fairly "
"confident in the installation and configuration of the package."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:609
msgid ""
"There's still plenty more to do to complete the overall network "
"installation, though it's downhill from here."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:610 origin/heimdal.txt:954
#, no-wrap
msgid "----------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:612 origin/heimdal.txt:956
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Notes about the keytab file:\n"
"----------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:618 origin/heimdal.txt:962
msgid ""
"Eventually, you'll want to add server daemon principles to the database and "
"extract them to the keytab file. You do this in the same way you created the "
"host principles. Below is an example (after you connect to the database "
"using kadmin)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:620
msgid "add --random-key ftp/belgarath.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:622 origin/heimdal.txt:966
msgid "(choose the defaults)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:624
msgid "ext ftp/belgarath.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:627
msgid ""
"Of course, make the appropriate substitutions for the hostname and "
"domainname."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:628
#, no-wrap
msgid "---------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:630
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating the Admin Access Control List (ACL):\n"
"---------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:636
msgid ""
"This step isn't necessary if you have no plans on remotely administering the "
"KDC server. If all you'll ever do is connect to the KDC database locally "
"using the \"kadmin -l\" command, you don't need to create an ACL "
"file. Though you should keep one thing in mind."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:646
msgid ""
"Any machine acting as a kerberos server (not just the KDC server, but any "
"server running kerberized daemons) must have a keytab file installed. We've "
"already created a basic keytab file for the KDC server, but no others. You "
"can create a keytab file for another machine locally using \"kadmin -l\", "
"but you must transmit it to the other machine using some sort of encrypted "
"method (or floppy disk, tape, CD or other media). If a keytab file is "
"transmitted from the KDC server to another server without encryption, the "
"keytab file can be compromised, leading to an entirely compromised kerberos "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:652
msgid ""
"Now, in a home network environment, this isn't too big a deal. But if you "
"are installing kerberos in a production environment where security is "
"important (it must be, why else install kerberos?), then anyone with a "
"packet sniffer can compromise your keytab file during transit if it's not "
"encrypted."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:655
msgid ""
"The solution is to remotely connect to the KDC database and extract a keytab "
"file for the remote server, or use scp, ssh or something along those lines."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:657
msgid "'Nuff said."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:659
msgid "Anywho, back to an ACL file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:661
msgid "Create a basic Access Control List (ACL) file with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:664
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cat > /etc/heimdal/krb5.acl << \"EOF\"\n"
"loginname@LFS.ORG   all\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:672
msgid ""
"Of course, substitute a valid principal and realm name. You may name the ACL "
"file anything you wish. It doesn't have to be krb5.acl. Heimdal, however, is "
"specific in the filename it uses as an ACL file. We put the ACL file in the "
"/etc/heimdal configuration directory, as this is more FHSish. To satisfy "
"Heimdal, we need to create a symbolic link with the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:674
msgid "ln -s /etc/heimdal/krb5.acl /var/lib/heimdal/kadmind.acl"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:678
msgid ""
"Insure that whatever name you used for the acl file in /etc/heimdal is the "
"name of the file in the symlink. Note /var/lib/heimdal/kadmind.acl is not "
"optional."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:685
msgid ""
"This is the most very basic ACL as possible. As you create user principals, "
"you may provide different access levels to each. For now, the principle you "
"identified above will have full remote administrative access to the KDC "
"database. You'll probably want to create \"admin\" principals. Read the man "
"pages and do some googleing on kerberos administration to find out more "
"about ACL's and the \"admin\" principles."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:686
#, no-wrap
msgid "-----------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:688
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Remote Access to the Master KDC Database:\n"
"-----------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:695
msgid ""
"Remote access to the KDC database is provided by the kadmin program. The "
"kadmin program requires the kadmind daemon to be functional on the KDC "
"server. The kadmind daemon is spawned on the KDC server by (x)inetd. I use "
"the following configuration in my /etc/xinetd.conf file (note - I use "
"tcp-wrappers)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:706
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"service kerberos-adm\n"
"{\n"
"    flags           = REUSE NAMEINARGS\n"
"    socket_type     = stream\n"
"    wait            = no\n"
"    user            = root\n"
"    instances       = UNLIMITED\n"
"    server          = /usr/sbin/tcpd\n"
"    server_args     = /usr/sbin/kadmind\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:709
msgid ""
"The kerberos-adm service port is identified in a standard LFS /etc/services "
"file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:712
msgid ""
"You can remotely connect to the master KDC database by the principle you "
"have already created (and provided access via the ACL) with the following "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:714 origin/heimdal.txt:934
msgid "kadmin -p loginname"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:717
msgid ""
"(this assumes Heimdal is installed, and /etc/heimdal/krb5.conf exists on the "
"remote machine)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:720
msgid ""
"After you create \"admin\" principles, you can remotely connect and "
"administer the database by simply using the \"kadmin\" command without a -p "
"option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:723
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Notes about the kpasswdd Daemon:\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:730
msgid ""
"Heimdal provides a front end program (kpasswd) to the KDC database which "
"allows end users (principals) to change their kerberos password. This "
"program relies on the kpasswdd daemon to be running on the KDC server. The "
"init script below will automatically start the kpasswdd daemon. The kpasswdd "
"daemon should not be run from (x)inetd."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:733
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Creating the KDC Server Init Script:\n"
"------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:736
msgid "To create an init script, issue the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:740
msgid ""
"cat > /etc/rc.d/init.d/heimdal << \"EOF\" #!/bin/sh # Begin "
"$rc_base/init.d/heimdal"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:744
msgid ""
"# Based on sysklogd script from LFS-3.1 and earlier.  # Rewritten by Gerard "
"Beekmans - gerard@linuxfromscratch.org # Heimdal bootscript submitted by "
"Randy McMurchy <LFS-User at mcmurchy.com>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:747
msgid ". /etc/sysconfig/rc . $rc_functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:757
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"case \"$1\" in\n"
"        start)\n"
"                echo \"Starting KDC Server Daemon...\"\n"
"                /usr/sbin/kdc &\n"
"        \t\tevaluate_retval\n"
"                echo \"Starting KDC kpasswdd Daemon...\"\n"
"                /usr/sbin/kpasswdd &\n"
"\t        \tevaluate_retval\n"
"                ;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:764
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        stop)\n"
"                echo \"Stopping KDC kpasswdd Daemon...\"\n"
"                killproc /usr/sbin/kpasswdd\n"
"                echo \"Stopping KDC Server Daemon...\"\n"
"                killproc /usr/sbin/kdc\n"
"                ;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:770
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        restart)\n"
"                $0 stop\n"
"                sleep 1\n"
"                $0 start\n"
"                ;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:775
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        status)\n"
"                statusproc /usr/sbin/kdc\n"
"                statusproc /usr/sbin/kpasswdd\n"
"                ;;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:781
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        *)\n"
"                echo \"Usage: $0 {start|stop|restart|status}\"\n"
"                exit 1\n"
"                ;;\n"
"esac\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:783
msgid "# End $rc_base/init.d/heimdal"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:788
msgid ""
"Change the permissions of the init script so that it is executable using the "
"following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:790
msgid "chmod 754 /etc/rc.d/init.d/heimdal"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:796
msgid ""
"I don't use the canned LFS bootscripts. I've created my own with a slightly "
"different directory structure and number ordering scheme. So I'm not really "
"in a position to create the necessary symlinks. Simply copy the format of "
"your existing symlinks and substitute the number of your choice for startup "
"and shutdown order."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:799
msgid ""
"You may also install the init script *and* associated symlinks by using the "
"instructions in the BLFS book. You'll find this in the heimdal-0.6.2 "
"section."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:803
msgid ""
"This wraps up the installation and configuration of the master KDC "
"server. If the KDC server will also be used to run kerberized daemons, some "
"of the following instructions will apply."
