#: origin/heimdal.txt:923
msgid ""
"(you may remove the [logging] section if you know the server will never "
"become a slave KDC server)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:932
msgid ""
"If you followed the instructions during the KDC server installation to "
"create an ACL, this step should be simple. First, as the root user (we're "
"going to create a file in /etc/heimdal and hopefully only the root user has "
"write access), connect to the KDC server using the kadmin program."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:940
msgid ""
"Use the login name you created earlier in the KDC server installation and "
"gave access via the ACL. (If you didn't create an ACL, you'll need to "
"connect to the database locally using the kadmin -l command. The steps are "
"the same, but you'll need to transfer the keytab file from the KDC server to "
"the remote server.) At the \"kadmin>\" prompt, issue the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:942
msgid "add --random-key host/remoteserver.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:946
msgid ""
"Of course, substitute a valid hostname and domainname. Leave the word "
"\"host\" as is. Accept the default values when prompted. When you're back at "
"the \"kadmin>\" prompt, issue the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:948
msgid "ext host/remoteserver.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:950 origin/heimdal.txt:970
msgid "Of course, substitute ......."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:953
msgid ""
"This should create a keytab and srvtab file in /etc/heimdal. Insure the "
"permissions are 600."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:964
msgid "add --random-key ftp/remoteserver.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:968
msgid "ext ftp/remoteserver.lfs.org"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:977
msgid ""
"Heimdal should now be installed and ready for use as a kerberized server.  "
"There's really not much to do to get the kerberized daemons "
"running. Telnetd, rshd and ftpd should not need anything in order for them "
"to work if they were previously running. Simply send a SIGHUP to the "
"(x)inetd process (kill -1 pid)  so it will reread the configuration "
"file. This isn't really necessary, but it will complain if something is "
"amiss."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:981
msgid ""
"If you haven't previously configured the telnetd, rshd, and ftpd daemons on "
"the machine, do so now by making the appropriate entries in (x)inetd.conf "
"and starting/signalling (x)inetd."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:984
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Configuring the kxd Daemon:\n"
"---------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:992
msgid ""
"To me, one of the coolest things with the Heimdal kerberos package is its "
"ability to securely forward X requests. The Heimdal rxterm and rxtelnet "
"programs are really cool. Using them, you can securely request an X session "
"by any user on any host. Logged in as user A on host A, you can request an X "
"session started by user B on host B to be displayed on user A's display.  "
"These programs rely on the Heimdal kxd daemon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:998
msgid ""
"The kxd daemon needs some configuration. First, there's no service port "
"assigned to the kx service in the /etc/services file. The port used in most "
"of the stuff I found while googleing about kerberos kxd is spoken for by the "
"IANA database information. So, you'll have to pick one. I used "
"1001. Whatever port you choose, make the appropriate entry in the "
"/etc/services file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1001
msgid ""
"Next, edit the (x)inetd.conf file to include an entry for the kx service. I "
"have the following entry and it works just fine (I use tcp-wrappers)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1012
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"service kx\n"
"{\n"
"    flags           = REUSE NAMEINARGS\n"
"    socket_type     = stream\n"
"    wait            = no\n"
"    user            = root\n"
"    instances       = UNLIMITED\n"
"    server          = /usr/sbin/tcpd\n"
"    server_args     = /usr/sbin/kxd\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1015
msgid ""
"Send a SIGHUP to (x)inetd and things should be good. This completes a basic "
"server setup."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1016
#, no-wrap
msgid "====================================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1018
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"6. USING KERBERIZED CLIENT PROGRAMS:\n"
"====================================\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1029
msgid ""
"To use the kerberized client programs (telnet, ftp, rsh, rxterm, rxtelnet, "
"rcp, xnlock) they must be installed on the client machine. You can probably "
"copy the programs and libraries from a machine that has had a Heimdal "
"install if the architecture is similar. Maybe someone will try it out. To "
"me, it's easier to just do an install of the package. Slow cpu machines "
"notwithstanding. The make alone on my production KDC server, an ancient AMD "
"P5-133mhz machine that Linux thinks is an i486 took over 3 1/2 hours! I "
"didn't cross-compile as I wasn't pressed for time and felt the workout was a "
"good test of the machine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1031
msgid "Ah hell, just do an install on the machine if you haven't already."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1035
msgid ""
"You can omit installing Berkeley-DB and cracklib and then use the "
"--disable-berkeley-db switch to ./configure if the machine will never be a "
"kerberos slave server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1039
msgid ""
"After the programs are installed you need an /etc/heimdal/krb5.conf "
"file. The instructions for creating the file earlier in the hint are valid "
"again. You can omit the logging section, if applicable (not a slave server)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1041
msgid "That's all there is to it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1050
msgid ""
"To run a kerberized program, you must first get a TGT. Use the \"kinit\" "
"program to get the ticket. After you've acquired the ticket, you can use the "
"kerberized programs to connect to any kerberized server on the network. You "
"will not be prompted for authentication until your ticket expires (default "
"is one day), unless you specify a different user as a command line argument "
"to the program. You may get tickets for several principals (users), if you "
"know the passwords, and bop along the network running program after program, "
"never having to provide authentication."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/heimdal.txt:1054
msgid ""
"The kerberized programs will connect to non kerberized daemons, warning you "
"that authentication is not encrypted. As mentioned earlier, only the ftp "
"program gave any trouble connecting to non kerberized daemons."
msgstr ""

